  "bio_raw": "Iram Mehrin is a Senior Lecturer of Applied Linguistics and ELT at the Center for Language Studies (CLS), University of Liberal Arts Bangladesh (ULAB). She has also worked as the coordinator of the Centre for Excellence in Teaching and Learning (CETL), ULAB and organized new faculty induction trainings and other Faculty Development Trainings such ‘Legal Certainties in Academia’ (Spring 2026) and ‘AI And Advanced Technologies for Academics’ (Summer, 2026). In addition to that, she has also functioned as an internal auditor at ULAB. She has studied Spanish Language and Culture at the Universidade de Santiago de Compostela, Spain as a recipient of the Catedra Inditex Scholarship from the Institute of Modern Languages, University of Dhaka. Furthermore, she is an assistant facilitator and moderator of MOOCs offered by World Learning, Global Development Division, US State Department. Her research and publications appear in leading national and international journals and Handbooks.",
  "stated_interests": [
    "Language teaching, applied linguistics, Education and identity, AI and higher education, inclusivity and social justice."
  ],
  "education": [
    {
      "raw": "Education\nMA - Applied Linguistics and English Language Teaching (ELT)\n, University of Dhaka.\nBA - English\n, University of Dhaka"
    }
  ],
  "publications_raw": [
    "Journal Articles\nMehrin, I.\n, Ahmed, T., Sultana, R. & Sultana, S. (2025). Indigenous ethnic students in the mainstream education of Bangladesh: Cultural misrecognition, linguistic inequality and social injustice. Journal of Language, Identity & Education. DOI: 10.1080/15348458.2025.2520429\nAhmed, T., Sultana, R.,\nMehrin, I.\n& Sultana, S. (2024). Transformative Multiliteracies Pedagogy and Sustainable Development : Investigating Govt. Primary Schools in Chattagram Hill Tracts. In M.O. Hamid, S. Sultana, & M.M. Roshid (Eds.), Language and Sustainable Development in Bangladesh: Policies, Practices, and Perceptions (pp. 38-56). Routledge.\nMehrin, I.\n(2024). Transglossia and virtual role-play: Bangladeshi youths’ virtual resistance against oppression. In S. Sultana, M.M.N. Kabir, M.Z. Haider, M.M. Roshid, M.O. Hamid (Eds.), Language in Society in Bangladesh and Beyond: Voices of the Unheard in the Global South (pp. 176-191). Routledge\nMehrin, I.\n(2022). Promoting learner autonomy through critical-thinking in Bangladeshi ELL classes: A CLIL approach. Journal of the Centre for English Teaching and Research (CETR), University of Dhaka, 1(1) Special (DU Centennial) Issue, 21-42\nMehrin, I.\n(2020). Promoting Critical Thinking through Cultural Topics in Bangladeshi Tertiary EFL Context. Journal of Nepal English Language Teacher Association (NELTA), 25(1), 1-17. https://nelta.org.np/nelta/uploads/web-uploadsfiles/NELTA%20Journal%202020.pdf\nMehrin, I.\n(2017). Autonomous Language Learning: Bangladeshi Undergraduates’ Attitude and Perceptions. BELTA (Bangladesh English Language Teacher Association) Journal, 1(1), 124-142. https://www.journal.belta-bd.org/journal/pdf/15ecfe2a6ab409.pdf"
